by bicycle but there is a rather large incline once you’re on the main road that leads into the city. That means that even people with reasonably good physical conditions will have a hard time pushing their bicycles up the hill. I did a power meter test last night to give you a rough idea. A power meter test reads something like 200-300 watt with an average of 230 watts. I managed up the hill at 5.7mph or 3.45kph. It’s quite steep and it’s safe to say that practically everyone moans and groans when they round one more turn.

My future neighbour was having their house built and there are a few newly built properties in the countryside. It’s a big combination of old and new and the people don’t seem too concerned with tradition over practicality (when at the gas station, one guy pointed to one entirely new building and asked, “so is that palácelord then?!”)

There was a huge smell of sewage in the air.  I’m unsure if this has to do with water treatment plants that are near by or is a natural part of the landscape (the smell is very similar to the Bioparque in Costa Rica where a city sewage system by the coast was under construction during the time I lived there).

The women in a kitchen in Yamaguchi wore aprons that said STEP. I died.  Lolz.
